The English translation of "Warum Jerome Powell gehen muss" is:  "Why Jerome Powell has to go"  This sentence implies that there is a reason why Jerome Powell (likely referring to Jerome Powell, a prominent American economist and former chairman of the Federal Reserve) needs to leave his position or role.
NEW YORK – U.S. President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Whom should he appoint as the head of the U.S. Federal Reserve – thus, to what could be the most powerful position in the world economy?
A wrong decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, thereby paving the way for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the reaction of political decision-makers to it had far-reaching political consequences; it exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting feeling of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There is a multitude of clichés why the current Federal Reserve chairman Jerome Powell should be confirmed in his position.
It would be a proof of impartiality.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
The sentence translated from German to English is: "We would need someone with experience to guide us through the recovery following the pandemic."
And so on.
The exact same arguments I had heard 25 years ago when I was the chairman of the economic advisory board to US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country has paid a heavy price for its decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little heed to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and refused Volcker a second term after he had succeeded in taming inflation.
Reagan owed a lot to Volcker, but he aimed for deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an adherent of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to goal conflicts are required.
How important is inflation in comparison to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that the markets are efficient, stable, fair, and characterized by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the USA always presented clearly articulated, but distinctly different viewpoints on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to populist delusions).
From my perspective, the Democrats justifiably worry about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis demonstrated that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Moreover, we know that traditionally, only under strained labor markets marginalized groups have been integrated into the national economy and wage differences have been reduced.
The coming years will likely be a test of every US bank chief.
The United States is already facing difficult decisions about what to do against inflation.
Are the most recent price hikes essentially a problem arising from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed consider the unemployment rate for African Americans, who have not yet returned to their pre-pandemic levels?
Would rising interest rates (and consequently an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While mispriced mortgage-backed securities with collateralized debt obligations played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even more pervasive and severe mispricing associated with financial assets linked to climate change.
What should the Fed do regarding this?
Powell is not the man for the hour.   (Note: A more idiomatic translation could be "Powell is not the man for the moment" or "Powell is not the man of the hour," depending on the context.)
Initially, he supported former President Donald Trump's deregulation agenda, thereby risking the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, despite other central bankers around the world having long since declared this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues do not fall under the mandate of the Fed, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Federal Reserve's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never encountered a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing that the economy currently needs.
A glaring lack of competition and the absence of adequate regulation already enable excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
However, every second-year student would have known that during a recession, you must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argues, Powell does not feel particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell’s tenure as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board has been characterized by a series of misjudgments regarding monetary policy tightening over the past decade, extending back to the “Taper Tantrum” of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the Federal Reserve's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policy has important distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early hike in interest rates can stifle growth, weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the most recent scandal involving stock trading by top Fed officials has undermined trust in the leadership of the central bank.
The apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest on Powell's part, including even the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has long troubled me.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Federal representative should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock transactions would appear improper.
The Fed resembles the US Supreme Court in certain respects.
This is meant to stand above politics, but since at latest Bush v. Gore we know that this is not the case.
-Trump has made this clear for everyone who still had doubts.
The Fed is supposed to be independent as well, but Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown, by following their party's agenda for deregulation, that this is also not the case.
However, while the central bank rate makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power traditionally concentrates in the hands of the central banker – much more so than with the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the chairman of the note issuance committee who decides what items come to the vote and which topics are deferred or pushed to the forefront.
The climate question is just an example where it is incredibly important who sits at the head of the table.
The USA need a central bank that is truly committed to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitively determined financial sector.
The sentence translated from German to English is:  "Those who believe that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far lack insight."
We neither need an ideologue like Greenspan nor a lawyer inclined towards Wall Street like Powell.
Needed is someone who possesses deep economic understanding and shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There undoubtedly is a multitude of people who fulfill these conditions.
But Biden does not have to look far to find someone who has already proven his skills.
Lael Brainard is already a member of the monetary policy committee, where she has demonstrated her expertise and earned the markets' trust – without compromising on her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chief who ensures continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but who also shares his economic and social program.
